\fs32 \cf0 3.	Hardware Requirements\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 \
The VSTs provided have been tested on MacOS 12.f, and Windows XX. The python scripts should be useable on any platform. The tracking system should be accurate to within 1 cm, and have ideally give total latency from movement to audio less than 20 ms, although latencies up to 100 ms are useable. The Vive tracker system requires the SteamVR software environment which is fully supported for Windows, but only early beta for MacOS. The full reference system consists of a Windows laptop running the tracking software, sending OSC messages via wire ethernet to a Macbook Air running the REAPER example session.  If the listener is going to move around, the loudspeakers should not be larger than the human head, to ensure that they are approximately omnidirectional in the CAP frequency range.  They should also preferably be supported on stands so they are surrounded by air as much as possible.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li397\fi-397\ri0\sb240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\fs32 \cf0 4.	Plugin use
\f1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs24 \cf0 \
The plugin receives audio on 32 channels, for a maximum of 32 audio objects. Metadata is received to control the position of these objects. The metadata can be sent by including a VISR Panner plugin for each object in the DAW session. Before the CAP plugin can be used, an 
\b array configuration file
\b0  must be loaded. CAP can work with any number and configuration of loudspeakers. Some example Stereo configurations are included in the VISR Production Suit distribution at  
\b VPS/resources/CAP/config
\b0 . The current configuration will be used by default next time the plugin is used. The array configuration contains the 3D position of the acoustic centres of the loudspeakers relative to a chosen origin. The example configuration 
\b CAPstereo2m.xml 
\b0 describes an array consisting of two loudspeakers facing forwards and with their low frequency acoustic centres 2 m apart. The coordinate centre is set 1.6m back from the mid point of the loudspeakers. This matches with the REAPER session described below.\
\
Listener tracking information is received using OSC messages : /x /y /z /yaw /pitch /roll. The message values must match the co-ordinates used in the array configuration, the VISR co-ordinate system. VISR uses the convention x forward (to stage), y left, and z up. The OSC parameters are normalised to the range -1 .. 1, which is the visible automation range in REAPER. The actual values mapping to the normalised range are:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	-1	1\
x	-10	10	metres\
y	-10	10	.	\
z	-10	10	.\
yaw	 -180	180	degrees\
pitch	-90	90	.\
roll	-180	180	.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
The tracker co-ordinates x, y, z should match the point midway between the ears, accurate to within 1 cm. \
\
Note the cross-over filters are optimised for the 44.1 KHz sample rate. They will work ok for 48 KHz, but very different rates shouldn\'92t be used.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li397\fi-397\ri0\sb240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\fs32 \cf0 5.	Using the HTC Vive Tracker system\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 \
Following the introduction of the Vive head mounted display, HTC have introduced a compact tracker device using the same tracking system. The tracker can be fixed to the head using brace. The following example is adapted from the inner part of a safety helmet:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 It is important that the sideways horizontal axis of the tracker is accurately aligned with the 
\b aural axis
\b0 , that is the line between the ears. The reference for the tracker is provided by the Vive Lighthouse. A single Lighthouse allows tracking over several metres with sufficient accuracy, although more Lighthouses can be used for a wider area. It should be angled downwards from ~2m height so that it has a clear path to the tracker. Either a stand or ceiling/wall mount can be used:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
The Lighthouse is usually best placed in a side corner of the listening area so that it does not obstruct movement.\
\
To extract tracker data, without needing a Vive HMD, we use the third party python 
\b openvr
\b0  library, combined with a python wrapper 
\b triad_openvr 
\b0 from Triad Semiconductors. We have extended the scripts in the wrapper to ease integration with the VISR system. Detailed instructions for installing the basic tracker system are given in the Appendix, and have been copied from an online article \
\
Once the basic system is working as described, the original wrapper can be replaced with the extended wrapper, located at 
\b VPS/resources/CAP/triad_openvr-master_DM 
\b0 An additional module is required for OSC messaging, which can be loaded by executing 
\b pip install python-osc 
\b0 in the Anaconda prompt window.\
\
Two configuration files are important for the correct working of the tracking system with the CAP plugin. The 
\b array configuration file
\b0  is an xml file containing the loudspeaker setup in the VISR co-ordinate system, and is part of the reproduction system. The 
\b frame map file
\b0  is based in the tracking system, and contains information to map the Vive co-ordinates to the VISR co-ordinates. Unfortunately, each time the tracker is powered up the Vive co-ordinate system can shift significantly, requiring an update to the frame map (the tracker will power off after 5 minutes of no movement). The wrapper extensions are designed to speed up the frame calibration. The two top level extension scripts for the user are:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 tracker_test_DM_measureArray.py\
tracker_test_DM_head.py\
