\fs32 \cf0 6.	REAPER Example Session\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 \
\
An example REAPER session is kept in a separate repository. For more information see the CAP section of the S3A website. The session can be used to test the system is working, and also learning how to produce a variety of different scenes. The session assumes you have the following VST plugins installed and available to REAPER: VISR Object Plugin, VISR Scene Master, VISR CAP Renderer. Once the session is loaded you will be presented with the Project Settings window. This reminds you to load the array configuration if it is not already set correctly, which is done by navigating to the file in the VISR CAP Renderer window. The window should already be open, and can be closed/opened by clicking on the FX button in the CAP renderer track. The default configuration file is 
\b CAPstereo2m.xml 
\b0 for two loudspeakers. Any number of loudspeakers can be used.\
\
A stereo audio device should be selected, if not already. The routing button on the master track gives access to a final stereo balance control. This is useful for trimming any slight imbalance in the audio output system. To help the balancing process, a noise generator is included in the master track. This can be switched on/off via the master track FX button. The sound levels at the loudspeakers can be compared with a simple phone based sound meter. It can also be useful to adjust the master balance while listening to head-tracked output.\
\
The session consists of a number of source tracks each with mono audio files with processed a VISR Object Panner plugin. The source audio streams are routed via track sends to the CAP Renderer track, and the object metadata generated by the panners is routed internally to the CAP Renderer. A number of separate examples are set up as separate sessions horizontally. A region can be selected by double clicking on the region bar. To help control the session quickly when giving demonstrations, the session has been made controllable over OSC using the 
\b TouchOSC
\b0  mobile device application . With TouchOSC on an Android phone it is simplest to create a hotspot and tether the reproduction computer. Once network settings have been set select the \'91simple\'92 layout.  If you scroll down the Project Settings window you will find notes showing how controls in the layout map to the REAPER session, including play/stop, region selection, volume, balance, extra reverberation on/off, tracking on/off, and filter band controls.\
\
Notes for each example are given below. Toggle the reverb button in TouchOSC to add live spatial reverberation that comes from all directions.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0
\b \cf0 1.	Woman - centre front\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 The voice of a woman talking is placed 1 m behind the centre point between the loudspeakers. If you move side to side this position should be apparent from the change of direction to the image. You can move up to the centre point and beyond and the image should stay stable. The image should also be stable when you rotate your head, except for a small range of angles on each side. The side instability is an unavoidable limitation of using two loudspeakers, but can be removed by adding a single frontal loudspeaker.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\b \cf0 2.	Woman - mid loudspeakers, Cello \'96 front\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 With two images at different positions, the overall scene becomes more convincing when you move around. As you approach the woman the volume increases until it reaches a limited value. You can walk around the woman or straight through. If you walk to the other side you can face the Cello, with the loudspeakers and woman behind you. If you go far enough forward, the high frequency content of the Cello disappears, because the VBIP renderer component can no longer operate.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\b \cf0 3.	Stereo music, Drums - behind\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 A stereo music file is reproduced using two distant virtual loudspeakers, so that the directions to the loudspeakers relative to you remain constant as you move around. Drums are played behind. The stereo image remains stable even when approaching the centre between the loudspeakers, and going past. Further forward the high frequencies drop out as in 2.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\b \cf0 4.	7.0 Movie audio\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Like 3. But with 7 virtual loudspeakers. The default sound clip is a very dynamic space battle scene taken from Star Wars. Switching tracking on/off illustrates how much Stereo-CAP can improve the experience compared with static stereo.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0
\b \cf0 5.	Drone \'96 circle\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 A bandlimited drone sound moves in a horizontal circle right around you. This is useful as an initial test case when setting up.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0
\b \cf0 6.	Woman \'96 circle\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Similar to 5. , but not bandlimited. The high frequencies can be heard when the image is within the span of the loudspeakers relative to the listener.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls15\ilvl0
\b \cf0 7.	Cello \'96 circle\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Similar to 6. This is a good example to try adding the live reverberation (use TouchOSC).\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls16\ilvl0
\b \cf0 8.	Cello \'96 behind\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 A fixed image behind, useful for L/R balance calibration. You can turn around, and the image should be stable in front of you.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls17\ilvl0
\b \cf0 9.	Cello - near front, Drums - far front\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Move from side to side. The change in directions to images (parallax) makes it clear that the drums are further away, and the cello is near.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls18\ilvl0
\b \cf0 10.	Drums - front, Reverb \'96 behind\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Walk up and down the middle between the loudspeakers, turning around. You will hear the cello and drums on opposite sides, with the high frequency band present for each depending where you are.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls19\ilvl0
\b \cf0 11.	Drums - back, Reverb \'96 front\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Like 10. , but reversed.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls20\ilvl0
\b \cf0 12.	Cello \'96 front\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Like 8.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\fi-426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls21\ilvl0
\b \cf0 13.	Stomps - circle above\
\pard\pardeftab720\li426\ri0\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Face away from the loudspeakers and make small movements with your head rocking as well as twisting. You may clearly hear stomps coming from the ceiling, moving along a semicircle. The effectiveness varies between people more than the other examples, which is unsurprising because height perception of real sources varies significantly between people.\
